4 to 42%.\nInternational Telegraph and Tele\nphone was up a point at 42%;\nHouston Oil up 1% at 64%; Na*\ntional Power and Light up a point\nat 41%.\nThe market was dull at the\nopening. U. S. lost at\n158 T. American Can was un\nchanged at 142%; A. T. T. down\nat 207%; General Electric up\nat 64; Radio and Radio-Keith\nunchanged at 28% and 25% re\nspectively.\nThe utilities were irregular, with\nStandard Gas down at 91%;\nUnited Corp, unchanged at 28%;\nUnited Gas Improvement up\nat 34%; American and Foreign\nPower down at 56%; Electric\nPower and Light down at 64%.\nWestinghouse sold down at\n131%. Southern Railway was up\n\u2019/a at 73%; Western Maryland\ncommon down at 19; New Ha\nven up at 101%; Erie un\nchanged at 38.\nBethlehem Steel opened\nhigher at 83\u2019/a. Vanadium was\nup at 63; Kennecolt Copper\nup at 29%; General Motors\nunchanged at 40; Nash Motor\ndown 1% at 31%; Standard Oil\nof N. J. down at 61%.\nPennsylvania Buys\nNew Haven Stock\nNEW YORK, Oct. 4.\u2014Pennsyl\nvania railroad and the Pennroad\nCorporation, its investment affili\nate, have acquired 74.925 shares\nadditional stock of New Haven\nrailroad since last April, accord\ning to the preliminary report of\nthe New England Railroad Com\nmittee submitted to the New En\ngland governors.\nRAILROAD VALUED\nThe Interstate Commerce Com\nmission today placed a final\nvaluation, as of June 30, 1918, of\n$41,417,800 on the Wheeling and\nLake Erie railroad. The property\nused but not* owned by the road,\nwas valued at $827,280. A valua\ntion of 01,155.810 was placed on\nand West Virginia, a\nMihftdiarF* i _ i i i\nDditly\nCHICAGO GRAIN FUTURES\nCHICAGO, Oct. 4 (1J9J8.)\nGrains closed firmer yesterday\nWheat was up 2c. com 1% to l%c\nand oats 1 to l%c. Rye finished\n2 to 2%c higher.\nWheat sold off to 1% at the\nstart with fairly heavy selling on\nweakness in Liverpool. Commis\nsion house buying, however, was\nagain in evidence and with pres\nsure not very heavy after the out\nset, the market hardened with\nlosses easily regained.\nThe English market was down\nI\u2019/ad due to a slow demand and\nreports of some rains in Australia.\nThe Winnipeg market opened\nto 1c lower, but at midday was\nto %c up. Domestic cash trade\nconditions continue strong. Ship\nments were liberal at 391,000 bu.\nGood rains were noted over most\nsections of the winter wheat belt.\nConditions in the Canadian sec\ntions were generally fair.\nThe Farmers\u2019 National Grain\nCorporation announced it is ready\nto make additional loans to mem\nber stockholders where needed to\nprotect margins for loans made\non grain in elevators. It is tak\ning this step, it was reported, be\ncause <rf a belief that present low\nprices will not continue.\nCom dropped off le at the\nstart but quickly rallied with\nwheat. Pressure was light and\nsupport fairly active. Country\nsales were not very heavy, and\nEastern buyers were active in\nthe cash market yesterday. Un\nsettled weather was reported over\nthe belt with showers in many\nsections.\nOats and rye followed the trend\nin other grains with offerings\nlight.\nEstimated carlot receipts were:\nwheat 20, com 92 and oats 39.\nWhfat\u2014 |Open.lHlgh.!Low.|Clo\u00bbe.\nDecember SI tel *3%\nMarch is T\nMay \u00abKI \u00ab9>\nCorn\u2014 1-\nDecember 82%' 85%l 82% 85%\nMarch 84%l 87% 84%\nMay 88% I 88% I ,84% 88%\nOats\u2014 I I\nDecember SB%l 3 8% 40%\nMarch <o%l 42% 40% 42%\nMay 142 i \u00ab3.h\nRye\u2014 I I\nDecember 504*1 jjOJil &3%\ny..:::::::::: U*l B ffil Ut\nCopper Price Falls\nLowest Since 1896\nNEW YORK. Oct 4.\u2014The w\nduction tn copper to 10 cents held\nthe attention of traders in the\nnon-ferrous metal markets last\nweek. The revised price is a new\nlow and the lowest price since\n1890.\nA number of the larger produc\ners were not disposed to push busi\nness. Output is expected to drop\nappreciably. _ esljm*\nSATURDAY\u2014OCTOBER 4\u20141030\nItte*-* Ntut End\nHl<h Low Dividend Mato Hl<b Low 11:41 Ch\u2019*o\n'47 19* Stow Warn 0h... 21*\n