 5* 5* s*+\n86 62 Willya Ov pt (7).. 63 63 63\n53* 42 WilsonACopf.... 43 43 43 +1\n72* 51* Woolworth Co 0) 67* 66 66*,+ 1*\n169 67* Worth Pump 97* 96* 96*+\n98 78 Worth Pumppf\u00df. 90 90 90 +2*\nY\n32* 12* Yellow Truck 8... 15* 15* 15*+\n47 32* Young SAW (3)... 36* 36* 36*+\n2,\n16* 5* Zenith Radio 6* 6* 6*-\n\u2022BxdiTidaaA tEx rights. t Plus 4% la stock.* I Pay\nable la scrip, 2 Plus in stock a Paid last year\u2014\u25a0no rsguiar\nrate. b Payable in stock. d Payable when earned. e Pay\nable in cash or stock. fPiae 10% in stock. sP.us 4% in\nstock, h Plus 2% In stock. I Pius 1% in stock, k Plus\n1% in stock, ns Plus 2-1% in stock, n Plus in stock,\no Subject to approval of stockholders, q Plus extras. sUnlt\nless than 100 shares.\nCANADA DEAL\nCONFIRMED\nMONTREAL, P. Q\u201e Oct. 4.\u2014ln\nthe absence of the acting Minister\nof Finance, E. B. Ryckman, and\nalso of the acting Deputy Minis\nter, Finance Department officials\ntoday were reticent about the re\nported negotiations under way for\na government refunding loan in\nNew York at SIM,M\u00bbJ)M at a\nlower rate of interest than the\nsecurities now call for.\nIn financial circles outside, how\never, the information volunteered\nwas that \"there are some such\nnegotiations and something in the\nreport an right.\u201d\nThe only maturing obligation\nthis year comprises $45,000,000 of\nthree-year notes, which come due\non December 1. These carry an\ninterest rate of 4 per cent. Con\nditions in the money market are\nthought to be such as may enable\nthe refunding of this obligation at\na lower rate of interest than 4\nper cent, and while a $100,MM),000\nloan would be $55,000,000 in ex\ncess of what is coming due, there\nis plenty of purposes to which the\nextra cash may be applied. Par\nticularly is this so in view of the\nexpenditures which are contem\nplated by the government on the\nauthority of Parliament and the\ncontrast of steady decline in the\nordinary revenues.\nFinancial Magazine\nFeature* Banker*\nTwo Washington bankers are\ncontributors to the current issue\n(rs \u201cTrust Companies,\u201d a financial\nmagazine. President Robert V.\nFleming of the Riggs National\nBank, writes comprehensively on\n\u201cGuarding the Bank Portfolio\nAgainst Speculative Hazards\u201d and\nNorman E. Towson, assistant\ntreasurer of the Washington Loan\nand Trust Company, deals with\nthe advantages derived from the\ninvestment department of the\nmodem trust company under the\nheading:\n\u201cRespending to PabfielMmand\nfor Safe Investment Guidance.\u201d\nColumbian I* Rare,\nBut of Little Value\nSpeaking of rare metals, the\nworld\u2019s supply of Columbian is\nonly about 25 pounds, the Bureau\nof Mines pointed out.\nThe metal is of little\nhowever, when compared to fold\nand otbsx precious minerals.\nGains in Trade Apparent,\nBut Seasonal\nIncreased retail and wholesale\nbuyinc and other seasonal fains\nare observed by Bradstreet and\nR. G. Dun\u2019s reviews of trade as\nthe business cycle swings into\nthe final quarter of the year.\nOther than these seasonal in\ncreases, brought about for the\ngreater part by cooler weather,\nno other indications of a wide\nspread business revival are dis\ncernible, the reviews show.\nBradstreet\u2019s states that the lack\nof moisture in the Southwest is\nunfavorable for the germination\nand growth of winter wheat, that\nthe recently Reported buying of\nsteel has lost some of its force\nwith the building up of stocks of\nthe metal and that exports of\nwheat and flour for the week\nended October 2 totaled 6,388,878\nbushels as compared with 9353,-\n097 the previous week and 4,848,-\n619 for the corresponding week\nof 1929.\nA continued large number of\ncommercial failures and a con\nsiderable reduction of bank clear\nings as compared with last year is\nreported by Dun\u2019s review. Its\nindex of commodity prices also\nshows that 39 of a total of 59\nchanges in wholesale prices were\nin a downward direction.\nCommodity Prices Uncertain\n\u201cThe final quarter of an un\nsettled year begins with wide\nspread and vigorous commercial\nrevival still deferred, although\nnot jrithout some indications of\nseasonal gain,\u201d Dun\u2019s review\nstates. \u201cThere is now, as might\nbe expected after rather a pro\ntracted period of uncertainty,\nmuch sensitiveness to the con\nflicting forces in operation and\nthe extensive scope and diversity\nof these factors accentuates their\ninfluence.\n\u201cAn equilibrium in commodity\nprices is yet to be reached, par\nticularly in the great agricultural\nGOUNTERISSUES\nADVANCE\nStocks responded generouly to\nthe improved tone exhibited by se\ncurities in yesterday\u2019s Over-the-\nCounter market. Activity broad\nened as the session progressed and\nfavorite issues were strong, with\nvolume of trading good.\nBank and trust company shares\nwere active, with brisk rallies of\nthe previous session continuing\nunabated. A slight reaction,\nlargely attributed to liquidation,\nresulted in an easier tone at the\nclose, but most all stocks showed\nmoderate advances at the end.\nBank of New York and Trust ad\nvanced 25 points and Brooklyn\nTrust 7. Manufacturers, Chem\nical, Bank of United States, Chase,\nIrving, New York Trust, Manhat\ntan, Bankers, Central Hanover,\nGuaranty, America, Public, Ameri\ncan Union and Lawyers Title\ngained.\nInsurance shares closed up frac\ntionally in moderate dealings, al\nthough a few issues, including Na\ntional Union, St. Paul Fire and\nMarine, Springfield Fire and Ma\nrine, American Reserve, Connecti\ncut General Life and National\nFire were easier. Home, Great\nAmerican, Phoenix, North River\nand Home Fire Securities were\nfractionally higher and Provi\ndence-Washington, Aetna Casualty\nand Surety and a few others were\nup 1.\nUtilities were more active, with\nprices generally better. The com\nmon shares inclined to ease off at\nthe close, but with little effect on\nthe day\u2019s advances. Among the\nfew issues to show slight losses\nwere Utica Gas and Electric,\nNorthern States Power, Delaware\nA common, Atlantic City Electric\nand Jamaica Water Supply.\nChanges in the industrial group\nwere mixed, with gains predomi\nnating. MacFadden Publications\npreferred. Gamewell Company pre\nferred, Petroleum Conversion, Na\ntional Licorice and Bancroft com\nmon were* better. American Dis\ntrict Telegraph of New Jersey\ncommon featured the communica\ntion list with a rise of 4 points,\nand Cincinnati and Suburban Bell\nTelephone advanced a point,\nSouthern and Atlantic Telegraph\nand Bell Telephone of Canada\nwere slightly easier. Bonds pre\nsented fractional gains, with trad\ning at a minimum. Other groups,\nwith the exception of investment\ntrusts, which were inclined to\nshow mixed price changes, were\nunchanged.\nPHILADELPHIA STOCKS\nBid Ask\nAmerican Storrs 42 \u00a94*\nBanker* Securities Carp pf 3\u00bb 41\nBell To! Co pf 115% \u00a9115%,\nE O Budd Mfx com 7 8\nE G Budd Mf< pt........ 42 \u00ab3\nBudd Wheel 9%\u00ae 9%\nCamden Fire\nCommonwealth\nFire Association 35 24%\nI Fischman Son* offered 24%.\nLake. Superior 9%# 10%\nMfr* Casualty 30 20%\nPhlla Elec Power 32%\u00a9 33\nPhil* Rapid Tran* 20 29\nPhlla Rapid Tran* pf.... MIMI\nReliance Insurance \u00a9l2\nVictory Insurance 9 IB\nWarner Ca...... it \u00a94O\nNEW YORK LIVE STOCK\nNEW YORK, Oct. 4.\u2014Cattle\u2014Re\nceipts. 1,6*4, Includlar 440 direct*.\nSteady. Two load* low, good rrade at\n(9-.7E. Mediums, 4*09 24. Plainer\nkinds, >8.54. Cow* and bulla\u2014Boarce\nat steady prices.\nVaalera and Calves\u2014Rsoeltrt* 2,470,\nIncluding 2,510 direct*. Vealer* in\nlight supply, steady. Good to choice.\n*l2 14.56. Mediums, 40,50 011 50. Call\nand common, *4 \u00a99. 'Sngall let of\nSoutherns, >lO.\nHog*\u2014Receipts, 1.410, Including 1,450\ndirects. Steady. 104-220 potw&A >14.25.\nSheep\u2014Receipts, 10.400. including\n8,340 directs. Two load* of lambs at\n*9.50. only offerings. Ono load Ohio\nwethers averaging 1M ponads st *4.l*.\n\u25a0wee sestnsl.\nstaples, securities markets have\ncontinued to lack stability, and\nsentiment has remained confused\nThose are among the major ele\nments acting as barriers to busi\nness progress, but they are Tamil\niar phases in times of readjust\nment. The point has been fre\nquently stressed that economic re\ncuperation was not likely to come\notherwise than slowly and un\nevenly, and the present abse.ee\nof, a broad advance is not sur\nprising. More than the ordinary\nfluctuation in the volume of trade\nappears in individual lines, from\nweek to week, giving the compos\nite situation a highly Irregular\naspect, and there is no general\ntrend in the various statistical\nbarometers. There is, however,\na naturally improved status in the\nretail field under the stimulus\nof autumn requirements, and the\nincreased activity in this channel\nhas been aided recently by cool\nweather over a considerable area\nof the country.\n\u201cConditions in manufacture, as\na whole, have not changed in\nmarked degree, although buying\nfor replenishment of stocks and\nsome forward purchasing induced\nby attractive prices has raised the\nlevel of production in certain in\nstances. In view of the unusual\ncircumstances which have pre\nvailed for many months, and\nwhich have been practically\nwgrld-wide, conservative opinion\ndoes not minimize the adjust\nments yet to be completed, even\nwhile recognizing the importance\nof the results already achieved in\nstrengthening the basic structure\nof business. Ultimately, there\nwill be a fuller response to the\nbetter fundamental position, end\nit will be facilitated by the abund\nance of funds available at excep\ntionally low rates. Instead of\nthe growing monetary tension of\na year ago, with abnormally in\nflated loans on speculative ac\ncount, the current trend is to\nward further ease in both re\nt9\nGROWTH SHALL\nIN FOODS\nBradstreet\u2019s food index number\nfor this week is 82.77, and com\npares with $2.71 last week, $2.77\ntwo weeks ago, and $3 2 7 for the\nweek ended October 3, 1929. This\nweek\u2019s number reflects a gain of\nthree-tenths of 1 per cent over last\nweek, but shows a loss of U 2 pet\ncent from the like week a year ago.\nThis index number, it may be ex\nplained, is the sum total of the\nprices per pound of 31 articles of\nfood 'out of the 43 foods.\nThe following table shows index\nnumbers of foodstuffs by weeks.\n1930 1929 1430 1929\nOct. 2. ..42.72 >3.27 Feb. 13... >3.07 43.44\nSept. 25.. 2.71 3.31 Feb. 4... 3.04 3.44\nSept. 18.. 2.77 3.33 Jan. 30... 3.08 3.42\nSept. 11.. 2.74 3.34'J*n. 23... 3.09 3.40\nSept. 4... 2.78 3.32 Jan. 14... 3.45 3.37\nAug. 28.. 2.78 3.33 Jan. 9... 3.07 3.30\nAug. 21.. 2.77 3.35 Jan. 2.... 3.94 3.30\nAug. 14.. 2.74 3.M 1430 IMB\nA\u00abtg. 7... 2.71 3.34 Dec. 24.. 3.13 1.20\nJuly 31.. 2.47 3.37 Dec. 19... 3.11 3.24\nJuly 24.. 2.47 3.34 Dec. 12... 3.11 3.30\nJuly 17.. 2.47 3.36 Dec. 5.... S.IS KM\nJuly 10.. 2.62 3.33 Nov. 28.. 3.14 8.35\nJuly 3... 2.70 3.33 Nov. 21.. 3.16 3.32\nJune 26.. 2.73 3,32 Nov. 14... 3.13 3.33\nJune 19.. 2.74 3.35 Nov. 7.... 3.14 8.32\nJun* 12.. 2.74 3.35 Oct. 31... 3.14 >.30\nJune 8... 2.80 3.33 Oct. 24... 3.23 3:33\nMay 29.. 2.79 3.34 Oct. 17... 3.25 3.24\nMay 22.. 2.79 3.32 Oct. 10... 3.24 3.37\nMay 15.. 2.80 3.33|0ct. 3.... 3.27 3.40\nMay 8... 2.85 3.36iSept. 24.. 3.31 3.41\nMay 1... 287 3.39!Sept. 19.. 3.33 3.44\nApr. 24.. 2.90 3.42 Sept. 13.. 3.34 3.47\nApr. 17.. 2.91 3.43 Sept. 5... 3.32 3.44\nApr. 10.. 2.94 3.43 Aug. 29.. 3.33 3.44\nApr. 3... 2.91 3.44 Aug. 22.. 3.35 3.41\nMar. 27.. 2.92 3.44 Aug. M.. 3.34 3.42\nMar. 20\u00bb. 2.93 3.46 Aug. 8... 3.36 3.38\nMar. 12.. 2.94 3.47 Aug. 1... 3.37 3.38\nMar. 4... 2.94 3.s2iju\u00bby 25... 3.38 3.80\nFeb. 27.. 2.95 3.52;ju1y 18... 3.34 8.41\nFeb. 20.. 3.01 3.51]\nThe compiling of Dun\u2019s index\nnumber as of October 1 reflects a\nreversal of the showing made a\nmonth earlier. Thus, this record\nof the movement of wholesale\nprices, which had risen slightly on\nSeptember 1, now discloses a reduc\ntion of 1.6 per cent, bringing the\nfigure down to a new low point for\nthis year and for a number of pre\nceding years. The renewed de\ncline, as was the case with the re\ncent small recovery, occurred\nmainly in the breadstuffs group,\ndue to a resumption of the fall of\nprices for the principal grains.\nOther classifications for foods ad\nvanced somewhat and metals rose\na trifle, but clothing and miscel\nlaneous articles again trended\ndownward. For the present week,\nrecessions again were largely in\nthe majority, 4 of a total of 59\nchanges being toward lower levels.\nA year ago, when easing in com\nmodity prices was becoming more\nnoticeable, 33 of the 55 alterations\nwere reductions, the review states.\nCHICAGO LIVE STOCK\nCHICAGO, Oct. 4 (T.N.B.).\u2014Hogs\u2014\nReceipt*, 14.000; market 10 to 15 eeat*\nhigher; top >10.15: bulk >7.75010 10;\nheavyweight. 39 65010.18; medium\nweight. 3* 75010.15; lightweight. 39.40\n\u00a99.90; light light*. 8*95010 65: peek\ning sow*. 87.5008.60; pigs, 38.28\u00a9\n9.25; holdover*. 5.000.\nCattle Receipts, 38.000; market\nsteady. Calve*\u2014Receipt* 1.800: mar\nket stesdv. Beef steers\u2014G\u00abw><i an-1\nchoice. 810012: common to medium\n46\u00a9*; yearling*. 87012: butcher cat\ntle. heifer*. >5.50012; cow*. 8-407 50:\nbull*. 85\u00a98: calves. 811013: feeder\nsteer*. *5.50 08; Stocker cows and\nheifer*. *4 50 07.\nSheep\u2014Receipt*, 15,060; market\neteadv; medium and choice lamb*.\n*7.50 0 8.26: eulls and common. 8*0*:\nyearling*. *504.75; common and chnice\newe\u00ab, *203.75: feeder lamb*. 9\u00ab9T\nSIK Ohio hog* 20 020 cants higher\nan quotation*.\nCalves\u2014Receipt 128 head. Market\nhigher. Calve*. *5 013.\nBALTIMORE GRAIN MARKET\nBALTIMORE. Oct, 4.\u2014Wheat\u2014Firm\ner; No: 2 reg winter export 85%e bushel\nNo. 3 re* winter garlicky domestic\n83%e; receipts. 18.94* \u00abbu\u00abhels; ship\nments 53.722 bushels.\nCorn\u2014Unsettled: No. 2 yellow domes\ntic carlots >1.0301.03 bushel; receipt*\n1.471